<paragraph blockId="38.[264,1323,433,699]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
Ants in this predominantly Neotropical genus nest in hollow dead twigs and other preformed plant cavities. Two species occur in California: 
<taxonomicName authority="Creighton" authorityName="Creighton" box="[918,1155,473,499]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pseudomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apache">
<emphasis box="[918,1031,473,498]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">P. apache</emphasis>
Creighton
</taxonomicName>
is widespread at middle and low elevations within the California floristic province, often nesting in branches of manzanita (
<taxonomicName box="[547,722,553,578]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Arctostaphylos" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[547,722,553,578]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Arctostaphylos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), while 
<taxonomicName authority="F. Smith" authorityName="F. Smith" box="[820,1072,553,579]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pseudomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallidus">
<emphasis box="[820,944,553,578]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">P. pallidus</emphasis>
(F. Smith)
</taxonomicName>
is confined to southern California.
</paragraph>
